      </section>

      <section id="who-should-buy">
        <h2>Who Should Buy</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Multi-device users</strong> who switch between laptop, tablet, and phone — the Keychron K8 and Logitech MX Keys S are ideal.</li>
          <li><strong>Typing enthusiasts</strong> who prioritize tactile feedback — the Ducky One 3 with Cherry MX Browns is unmatched.</li>
          <li><strong>Office professionals</strong> who need quiet typing — the Logitech MX Keys S at 42 dB is the quietest option.</li>
          <li><strong>Travelers</strong> who need a slim keyboard — the NuPhy Air75 at 22mm thick fits in any bag.</li>
          <li><strong>Keyboard enthusiasts</strong> who want premium build and customization — the Keychron Q1 with QMK/VIA is the enthusiast pick.</li>
          <li><strong>Mac users</strong> who want mechanical switches with Mac layout — the Keychron K8 has dual Mac/Windows keycaps.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="who-should-avoid">
        <h2>Who Should Avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Competitive gamers</strong> who need sub-1ms latency — use a wired keyboard like the Ducky One 3, not Bluetooth models.</li>
          <li><strong>Numpad users</strong> — the Keychron K8 (TKL), NuPhy Air75 (75%), and Keychron Q1 (75%) lack a numeric keypad. Get the MX Keys S or Ducky One 3 full-size instead.</li>
          <li><strong>Budget shoppers under $50</strong> — see our <a href="/best/best-budget-mechanical-keyboard/">budget mechanical keyboard roundup</a> instead.</li>
          <li><strong>Users who hate RGB</strong> — all keyboards except the Ducky One 3 have RGB. Turn it off in settings if it bothers you.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="final-verdict">
        <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
        <p>Based on product documentation analysis and specification comparison, the <strong>Keychron K8</strong> remains our top pick for most buyers. At $79, it delivers the best combination of wireless connectivity, hot-swap switches, battery life, and value. It is the keyboard we recommend to most people asking "what mechanical keyboard should I buy?"</p>
        <p>The <strong>Logitech MX Keys S</strong> is the best productivity keyboard, with unmatched multi-device integration and quiet operation. The <strong>Ducky One 3</strong> offers the best pure typing feel for enthusiasts who do not need wireless. The <strong>NuPhy Air75</strong> is the best low-profile option for travelers. The <strong>Keychron Q1</strong> is the premium pick for users who want the best build quality and customization.</p>
        <p>Whatever you choose, a mechanical keyboard is an investment in comfort and productivity that pays for itself in reduced finger fatigue and improved typing accuracy. See our complete <a href="/best/best-mechanical-keyboard/">best mechanical keyboards</a> guide for more options.</p>
      </section>

